    EDITORIAL FRAMING
    ─────────────────
    Keep the voice warm, concrete, and tactile — this is a story about clay under fingernails, not capital-C craftsmanship. Lead with the texture of the room (a clay-dusted studio, herbal tea on a Thursday, wine on a Saturday) and let the contrast between weekday and weekend formats do the structural work. Resist the urge to lionise — Perth Pottery Co reads as approachable rather than auteurist, and the framing should match. A short profile (600–800 words) works better than a long feature; consider a Q&A with Elizabeth if the writer can secure access, or a first-person try-it dispatch where the writer takes a single class and reports back. Avoid superlatives the data doesn't support (oldest, only, best). The deliberate choice to skip the wheel is the most interesting craft angle on the record — it's worth foregrounding.

